Brexit, and then what?
NEW YORK – It will take a lot of time for Britain, Europe, and the entire world to digest the implications of the UK's "Brexit" referendum.
The deepest consequences will depend, of course, on the European Union's response to the UK's withdrawal.
Most people initially believed that the EU would not "cut the branch it was sitting on": after all, a mutually amicable divorce seems to be in everyone's interest.
But the divorce – as is often the case – could become complicated.
The mutual benefits of commercial and economic integration between the UK and the EU are reciprocal, and if the EU took seriously its belief that greater economic integration is desirable, its leaders would seek to ensure that ties remain as close as possible given the circumstances.
Or, Jean-Claude Juncker, the architect of massive tax avoidance strategies for companies in Luxembourg and now President of the European Commission, seems to adopt a hard line: "Out means out," he declared.
This instinctive reaction may be understandable, given that Juncker could be seen as the one who presided over the first step of the EU's dissolution.
It argues that, to dissuade other countries from leaving, the EU must not accept any compromises, offering the UK barely more than what it guarantees under World Trade Organization agreements.
In other words, Europe should not be kept united by the advantages it offers its members, which far exceed its costs.
The economic prosperity, sense of solidarity, and pride in being European are not enough, according to Juncker.
No, Europe must be maintained through threats, intimidation, and fear.
This position does not take into account a lesson that is clearly apparent both in the Brexit vote and in the Republican primaries in the United States: a significant portion of the population has suffered greatly in recent times.
The neoliberal agenda of the past four decades may have been good for the top 1%. but not for the rest of the population.
I had predicted for a long time that this stagnation would have political consequences.
This day has now arrived.
On both sides of the Atlantic, citizens consider that trade agreements are the source of their woes.
While it is an excessive simplification, it is understandable.
Today's trade agreements are negotiated in secret, ensuring good representation of business interests but excluding ordinary citizens or workers entirely.
Without surprise, the results were one-sided: the negotiating position of workers has weakened further, thereby exacerbating the effects of legislation that diminishes union power and employee rights.
While trade agreements have played a role in creating these inequalities, many other factors have contributed to tilting the political balance in favor of capital.
The rules of intellectual property, for example, have increased the power of pharmaceutical companies to raise prices.
Or, any increase in market power for companies implies in fact a decrease in real wages – an increase in inequalities that has become a feature of most advanced countries today.
In many sectors, industrial concentration is on the rise – and so is market power.
The effects of stagnation and real wage cuts were added to those of austerity, which threatened cuts in public services that many low- and middle-income workers depend on.
The economic uncertainty for workers, when combined with migration, has created a toxic mix.
Many refugees are victims of the wars and oppression to which the West has contributed.
Providing aid is a moral responsibility for all, but especially for former colonial powers.
And yet, despite the fact that many would deny it, an increase in the supply of unskilled labor – as long as we are dealing with normally downward-sloping demand curves – leads to a decrease in equilibrium wages.
And when wages cannot decrease, unemployment increases.
This is particularly worrying in countries where poor economic management has already led to high levels of overall unemployment.
Europe, in particular the eurozone, has been poorly managed in recent decades to the point that its average unemployment rate is now double-digit.
Unrestricted migration in Europe means that countries which have more successfully reduced unemployment will inevitably end up hosting more than their fair share of refugees.
Workers in these countries bear the cost of depressed wages and higher unemployment, while employers benefit from cheaper labor.
The burden of refugees, unsurprisingly, is borne by those least able to shoulder it.
Of course, there is a lot of discourse about the net benefits of immigration.
For a country offering a low level of guaranteed benefits – social security, education, healthcare, etc. – to all its citizens, this can be the case.
But, for countries providing a decent social safety net, the opposite is true.
The result of all this wage pressure and cuts in public services has been the erosion of the middle class, with similar consequences on both sides of the Atlantic.
Middle-class and working-class households have not benefited from economic growth.
They understand that banks caused the 2008 crisis; but they then saw billions poured into bank bailouts, and insignificant amounts to save their homes and jobs.
While the median real (inflation-adjusted) income for a full-time male worker in the United States is lower than it was four decades ago, the electorate's anger should come as no surprise.
Moreover, politicians who promised change have not met expectations.
Citizens knew the system was unfair, but they began to see it as even more rigged than they had imagined, thereby losing what little trust they still had in the ability or willingness of traditional politicians to fix it.
This is understandable: the new politicians shared the perspectives of those who had promised that globalization would benefit everyone.
However, a vote of anger does not solve problems and may instead lead to a political and economic situation that is even worse.
It goes without saying if one responds with anger to a vote.
Forgetting the past is a fundamental principle in economics.
On both sides of the Channel, politics must now seek to understand how, in a democracy, the political establishment managed to do so little to address the concerns of many citizens.
Each EU government must now consider the improvement of ordinary citizens' well-being as its primary objective.
More neoliberal ideology will not help.
And we should stop confusing objectives with means: for example, free trade, if well-managed, could bring greater shared prosperity; but if mismanaged, it will certainly reduce the standard of living for many – perhaps the majority – of citizens.
There are alternatives to current neoliberal provisions that can create shared prosperity, just as there are alternatives, such as the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership proposed by US President Barack Obama, that would cause much more harm.
The challenge today is to learn from the past, in order to adopt the former and avoid the latter.
